​​Business Context	2 
Explain the background of the project, why it exists, and the real‑world problem it solves.
Do: Summarise the situation, industry, and purpose in 3–4 sentences

​Client Brief Review	2  
Show you understand what the client asked for and what success looks like.
Do: Highlight key requirements, goals, and expectations from the brief.

​Stakeholders	2 
Identify everyone affected by or involved in the system.
Do: List primary (users) and secondary (admins, managers) stakeholders with their interests.

​Constraints	3 
List the limitations that affect the project.
Do: Mention time, budget, technology, skills, legal, and resource constraints.

​Empathy Mapping	3 
Show understanding of the user’s feelings, needs, and behaviours.
Do: Summarise what users think, feel, say, do to guide design decisions.

​SWOT Analysis	4 
Analyse strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats of the solution.
Do: Provide 2–3 bullet points per section.

​User Stories & Acceptance	5 
Describe features from the user’s perspective and how you know they work.
Do: Use the format: As a [user], I want [feature], so that [benefit] + clear acceptance rules.
Acceptance: 

Management: 

Filtering and Searches: Users should be able to filter the type of service or product they are looking for to make the process of finding I easier or the use of the search bar for specific things. 

Display and Accessibility: 

Screen Compatibility: The home page displays correctly and proportional to all devices, screen sizes; ensure the layout is maintained on all support devices. 

Readability: Ensure that text and images are appropriate and considerate, meeting the accessibility standards if WCAG. 

Interactivity and Features:  

Navigation: Users can navigate through different products and services in an efficient manner depending on the device they are using (e.g. swiping for mobile, scrolling for computers etc.  

Search and Filtering: Users can search for services and products and filter what they are attempting to search for based on category, date posted and post information  

Notifications: Users can be notified on products they might be interested in depending on their preferences. 

​Functional & Non-Functional Requirements	6-7 
Functional = what the system must do.
Non‑functional = how well it must perform.
Do: List 8–12 requirements split into both categories.

​Decomposition of Requirements	8 
Break big requirements into smaller, manageable tasks.
Do: Turn each requirement into sub‑tasks or components.

​KPI’s & User Acceptance	9 
Define how success will be measured and how users confirm the system works.
Do: Include measurable KPIs (speed, accuracy, usability) + acceptance tests.

​Proposed Solution	10 
Give a high‑level overview of the system you plan to build.
Do: Summarise the architecture, tools, and main features.

​Description of the Proposed Solution	10 
Explain how the system works in more detail.
Do: Describe the workflow, pages, backend logic, and user interactions.

​Justification	7 
Explain why your chosen solution is the best option.
Do: Compare alternatives and justify your tech choices (e.g., Flask, HTML/CSS).

​Meet the Client and User Needs	7 
Show how your solution satisfies the brief and user expectations.
Do: Link features directly to client requirements and user stories.

​Risks, Mitigation & Wider Issues	8 
Identify risks and how you will reduce them.
Do: Include technical, security, ethical, and project risks with mitigation steps.

​Regulatory guidelines and legal requirements	9 
Show awareness of laws and standards relevant to your system.
Do: Mention GDPR, accessibility, data protection, and security requirements.

​Appendix	10​ 
Store supporting evidence and extra materials.
Do: Include diagrams, code snippets, test logs, assets lists, and research.


